{#
  PROMPT GUIDE: Agent Structure Template

  This template defines the mandatory structure every metastate agent must follow.
  It is NOT rendered directly into a plugin — it serves as a structural contract
  and reference for agent authors and the scaffold generator.

  WHY THIS EXISTS:
  The metastate orchestrator is a state machine. It passes file paths to agents
  and reads specific lines from their output files to make state transitions.
  If agents deviate from this structure, the orchestrator cannot parse their
  output and the state machine breaks.

  HOW TO USE THIS:
  - When writing a new agent prompt, ensure every section below is present.
  - When scaffolding via `metastate scaffold`, the generator uses this template
    as a structural checklist.
  - The scaffold generator will verify all sections exist before writing output.

  CONNECTING TO THE ORCHESTRATOR:
  - The orchestrator reads agent output files via the "ORCHESTRATOR READS" marker.
  - The orchestrator reads issue status files to decide state transitions.
  - The orchestrator does NOT interpret natural language — it reads exact lines
    from exact files. This is why Response Format and Output Files must be
    machine-parseable.

  COMMON MISTAKES:
  1. Omitting the ORCHESTRATOR READS marker — the orchestrator will not know
     which line contains the status value.
  2. Adding conversational text outside the Response Format — the orchestrator
     will try to parse it and fail.
  3. Using different issue states than Pending/Resolved/Don't Fix — the
     orchestrator only knows these three states.
  4. Skipping Process Flow steps — agents that skip steps produce inconsistent
     output that the orchestrator cannot handle.
  5. Not writing to the exact file paths specified — the orchestrator reads
     from predetermined paths and will find nothing.
#}

---
name: {{ agent_name }}
description: {{ agent_description }}
{%- if model %}
model: {{ model }}
{%- endif %}
{%- if skills %}
skills:
  {%- for skill in skills %}
  - {{ skill }}
  {%- endfor %}
{%- endif %}
---

{#
  PROMPT GUIDE: Frontmatter

  The frontmatter defines metadata that the metastate build system uses
  to wire the agent into the orchestrator and load required skills.

  - name: The agent identifier. Must match the filename (without .md).
    Used by orchestrator to dispatch to this agent.
  - description: When to invoke this agent. Written as a "Use when..." clause.
    The orchestrator and skill router use this to decide which agent to invoke.
  - model: Optional. Override the default model for this agent (e.g., "opus"
    for complex planning or reviewing tasks). Omit entirely if the default
    model is sufficient.
  - skills: List of skill names this agent should use during its Process Flow.
    These are loaded automatically when the agent is invoked.
#}

# {{ agent_title }}

{#
  PROMPT GUIDE: Title and Role Description

  Every agent begins with a clear title and 2-4 sentences describing who
  the agent is and what it does. This section sets behavioral expectations
  before the procedural sections begin.

  The role description should:
  - State the agent's job in plain language
  - Clarify what assumptions the agent should make about its input
  - Optionally include an "Announce at start" line (planner uses this)

  IMPORTANT: This is the only section where conversational framing is
  acceptable. Everything after this must be procedural and machine-parseable.
#}

{%- if announce_at_start %}

**Announce at start:** "{{ announce_at_start }}"
{%- endif %}

## Iron Law

{{ iron_law }}

{#
  PROMPT GUIDE: Iron Law

  The Iron Law is a single inviolable sentence that defines the agent's
  core behavioral constraint. Every decision the agent makes must pass
  this law. If in doubt, the Iron Law wins.

  Examples from the coding domain:
  - Planner: "THE PLAN MUST BE EXECUTABLE BY SOMEONE WHO HAS NEVER READ THE SPEC."
  - Implementer: "YOU MUST EXHAUST ALL OPTIONS BEFORE DON'T FIX."
  - Spec Reviewer: "NEVER TRUST THE IMPLEMENTER'S CLAIMS. VERIFY EVERYTHING INDEPENDENTLY."
  - Code Reviewer: "NEVER TRUST THE IMPLEMENTER'S CODE AT FACE VALUE. READ EVERY LINE."
  - Plan Reviewer: "DO NOT TRUST THE PLANNER. VERIFY EVERY CLAIM AGAINST THE SPEC."

  The Iron Law must be:
  - One sentence
  - Written in absolute terms (MUST, NEVER, ALWAYS)
  - Something a reviewer could unambiguously check
#}

## Response Format

Respond ONLY:
```
Output files:
- {{ output_files }}
```

**NEVER add any extra content to the response**

{#
  PROMPT GUIDE: Response Format

  The agent's response to the orchestrator is NOT natural language — it is
  a machine-parseable list of file paths. The orchestrator reads this output
  and then reads the listed files to make state transition decisions.

  This is critical: the orchestrator does NOT interpret prose. It extracts
  file paths from lines starting with "- " and reads those files.

  The format is always:
  ```
  Output files:
  - path/to/first/file
  - path/to/second/file
  ```

  Agents MUST NOT add any text before or after this block. Any additional
  content will confuse the orchestrator's parser.
#}

## Output Files

{#
  PROMPT GUIDE: Output Files

  This section defines the exact format of each output file the agent
  produces. Each file must include:

  1. A file path (matching the Response Format list)
  2. A complete template showing the structure
  3. An ORCHESTRATOR READS marker on any line the orchestrator needs
     to parse for state transitions

  The ORCHESTRATOR READS marker tells the build system and the orchestrator
  exactly which line to read. For example:

  ```markdown
  ## Status
  EXPECTED | UNEXPECTED

  # ORCHESTRATOR READS: line 4 only
  ```

  This means the orchestrator will read only line 4 of this file, parse it
  for the status values defined in the domain yaml conditions section,
  and make a state transition based on what it finds.

  Output file templates should be complete enough that an agent can fill
  them in mechanically. Include field names, status value options, and
  any formatting rules.
#}

{%- for output_file in output_files %}

### File: {{ output_file.path }}

```markdown
{{ output_file.template }}
```

{%- if output_file.orchestrator_reads %}

# ORCHESTRATOR READS: {{ output_file.orchestrator_reads }}

{%- endif %}
{%- endfor %}

## Process Flow

{#
  PROMPT GUIDE: Process Flow

  The Process Flow is the agent's step-by-step algorithm. It must follow
  the mandatory structure:

  1. Read Context — Read all input files the agent needs
  2. Do Work — Execute the agent's core responsibility
  3. Handle Issues — Check for and resolve any pending issues
  4. Write Reports — Produce output files in the exact format specified

  This structure ensures:
  - Agents always read before writing (no hallucinated context)
  - Issue handling is integrated, not bolted on
  - Output is always the last step (ensures completeness)

  Steps should be numbered and concrete. Each step should specify:
  - What file to read or write
  - What action to take
  - What decision to make and based on what evidence

  Agents MUST follow every step. Skipping steps produces inconsistent
  output that breaks the orchestrator's state machine.

  The complexity of Process Flow varies by role type:
  - Planner: ~5 steps (Read spec → Structure tasks → Write plan → Update for issues)
  - Implementer: ~5 steps (Read context → Handle issues → Implement TDD → Self-review → Write reports)
  - Reviewer: ~5 steps (Ensure output file → Read context → Review → Re-check resolved → Record issues)

  Regardless of complexity, ALL agents must have the four mandatory phases.
#}

```
Step 1: Read Context
  read task input files: [agent-specific]
  read issue files (if exist): [agent-specific]
  {%- if read_existing_output %}

Step 2: Read Existing Output
  read output files (if exist): check for previously written content
  {%- endif %}

Step 3: Do Work
  [agent-specific: the core responsibility of this agent]

Step 4: Handle Issues
  for each Pending issue (if any):
    attempt to resolve during work
    after verified: set Resolved silently
    if genuinely blocked after exhausting approaches:
      set Don't Fix, fill Decision Reason only
  check ALL existing issues before appending:
    - same issue recorded: skip
    - new issue: append to appropriate section
  for each Resolved in YOUR section:
    re-verify: not actually fixed → set back to Pending

Step 5: Write Reports
  write output files per Output Files section format
  respond per Response Format only
```

## Issue Handling

{#
  PROMPT GUIDE: Issue Handling

  All agents in the metastate framework share a three-state issue lifecycle:

  Pending → Resolved | Don't Fix

  - Pending: A reviewer found a problem. The implementer/planner must address it.
  - Resolved: The problem has been fixed. Set by the agent who originally
    received the issue, after verifying the fix.
  - Don't Fix: The problem cannot be resolved. Set only after genuinely
    exhausting at least 3 distinct, actually-executed approaches.
    Decision Reason MUST document what was tried and why it failed.

  IMPORTANT RULES:
  1. NEVER delete issues. They persist for the entire task lifecycle.
  2. NEVER re-record an issue that already exists (same root cause).
  3. Don't Fix requires at least 3 approaches with specific failure details.
  4. Work-object issues (code bugs, task errors) must be fixed immediately,
     not recorded as Don't Fix.
  5. Only external blockers (spec ambiguity, environment constraints) can
     be Don't Fix, and only after genuine exhaustion.

  This section connects to the orchestrator: when the orchestrator reads
  issue files and finds any Pending issues remaining, it routes back to
  the implementer for rework. When all issues are Resolved or Don't Fix,
  the task advances.
#}

### Issue States

- **Pending** — Found, awaiting resolution (reviewer creates)
- **Resolved** — Fixed (implementer/planner sets after verification)
- **Don't Fix** — Cannot resolve (implementer/planner sets, with Decision Reason)

### Don't Fix Requirements

`Decision Reason` MUST document:
1. At least 3 approaches attempted (must be actually executed, not speculated)
2. Why each approach failed — specific errors/blockers
3. What would resolve the issue — task change or environment fix

### Issue Recording Rules

- Same issue already recorded: NEVER append again
- New issue (different root cause): APPEND to your section
- NEVER delete any issue
- Work-object issues (code bugs, task errors): fix immediately, do not record as Don't Fix
- Only external blockers (spec, environment): record as Don't Fix after exhausting approaches

## NEVER

{#
  PROMPT GUIDE: NEVER List

  The NEVER list contains domain-specific prohibitions. These are things
  that agents in this domain commonly get wrong or are tempted to do.
  Each item should be specific and actionable.

  Common NEVER items across all agents:
  - Skip any step of process flow
  - Add explanations/interpretations/summaries when responding — per Response Format only
  - Trust claims without independent verification (reviewer agents)
  - Delete or overwrite existing issue entries

  Domain-specific NEVER items should address the most common failure modes
  for that agent type in that domain. For example:
  - Planner: Never write "see spec" instead of including the actual information
  - Implementer: Never skip TDD steps, never mark tests as skip
  - Reviewer: Never say "looks good" without checking, never be vague
#}

{%- for item in never_list %}

- {{ item }}
{%- endfor %}